segments.text: First, Mr. Jenkins, would you tell us something about your early life, including the names of your parents, when and where they were born and when and where they died, when you were born, and what schools you attended before you went to Texas A&M?
My father, A.G. Jenkins, was born in Tennessee.
He came to Texas in 1855 and settled in Burleson County, right across the river there from College Station.
He was a veteran of the Civil War, Confederate veteran.
I can explain that.
There's very few people living now whose father was in the Confederate Army, but he was.
And the reason that
I explained that was, his first wife died and then he married again and he married my mother who was 20 years younger.
And then I was the youngest child of his second family.
When he got out, I like to tell this about him, he was quite a pioneer.
When he got out of the service, he was captured at Siege of Vicksburg.
He was captured at Vicksburg and sent to prison at Rock Island, Illinois.
When he got back to Burleson County, in 68, he and some other former Confederate boys got a bunch of cattle, two-year-old steers.
Drove them to California and sold them as four-year-old steers.
Two years on the range.
a great man he was.
My mother was born there in Grosvenor.
And I was born in Caldwell in 1895.
Your mother's name was what now?
Mary, Mary King.
Mary King.
Mary King.
And what about the dates of your mother's birth?
Yes, my mother was born in, my father was born in
I was 45, and my mother was born in 65.
And my father died in 1917, the year I was a senior at A&M, and my mother died in 1922.
Were you born in Caldwell?
In Caldwell.
And you went to the public schools there?
That's right.
What factors were involved in your choice of A&M as a college?
I was seeking an agricultural course, and that close by, and was familiar with the school.
I take it you'd been there several times.
Oh yes, been on the Model T. We traveled to Baltimore on Friday.
I finished high school in 1913.
And that would be the football games that you went to?
Yeah.
What procedures did you go through to be admitted to the school?
Did you have to take a test of some sort?
No, our high school was affiliated with it.
We didn't have to take any tests.
You just appeared there and enrolled.
Did you have to apply and be accepted as you do today?
Yes, I guess so.
Yeah, we went over there two or three days before the deadline.
Well, what I'm getting at is today kids apply for admission to the school months and months before and then they get a letter saying you've been accepted.
No, we just went in there and signed up.
That was it.
This may be a little bit immaterial since you were somewhat familiar with the campus, but what was your immediate reaction when you were enrolled and settled into school at A&M?
Well, I was very proud of it.
I was very much impressed with the military.
I think back in those days, I think a student
got as much or more benefit, if I'll use the word correctly, from his military as he did from his academic.
The military back when I was there, they were right on a par with West Point in military training, military discipline.
We walked the post and mounted the guard every morning.
and it was supervised by West Point officers and they really cracked the meat of West Point out of it.
You couldn't get out of your room at night.
You had to stay in your room and study.
You had to march to all the meals.
You had to make revelry.
So you would say then the military kind of taught you regularity in
in a way that a civilian school could not have done.
Oh yes, I think the military was, the strict military was a wonderful thing.
Any boy that could take it, a lot of them would drop out like they do out of West Point now.
Would you say more of them dropped out because they couldn't take the military than because they couldn't pass the grades?
No, I guess I wouldn't know.
Some of both.
That's right.
There wasn't too many dropped out, but I do know that they resented hazing, and some of them couldn't take the hazing, and some of them didn't like the military, different things.

Could you describe, say, a typical day during the years that you were there, including the time you got up and the procedure for getting up, the hours you spent in class, the time you spent doing other things, such as drilling or sports or something, and then the procedure of going to bed?
Reveille blew it around 6 o'clock in the morning.
One time it was dark.
You had five minutes to get your clothes on and get out in front of the barracks and a Reveille call.
Roll was called.
And we'd have calisthenics at Reveille.
For how long?
Short time, maybe 15 minutes or less.
And then we'd go back up to our rooms and clean up our rooms, police our rooms for inspection.
And then we would first call for breakfast.
Maybe it's 45 minutes or something after we got up there.
And we went down and formed in formation again for breakfast.
And watched the breakfast.
And while we had breakfast, our rooms were inspected.
You had pretty much of an assigned seat at breakfast or at all meals?
Yes, we were in a company there.
We'd march in there as a company, and that company would sit together in Speezer Hall.
Then after breakfast, why, those classes started at 8.
Did your companies reform after breakfast?
No.
No, we didn't reform.
As we got through eating, we'd go back to
dormitory, and then the first call for classes, all this was done with a bugle.
First call to classes, if you had an eight o'clock class, I'd report to class.
Then you had four hours of class in the morning, go back at noon, and then the... By back, you mean to your dormitory?
Back to your dormitory.
Then the...
a mess call for noon meal.
And you formed a formation again and marched into Springsville Hall.
And after that, well, you'd go back and then you'd have your laboratory cases in the afternoon.
So then we drilled, we had drilled
three times a week.
I'd say it was from about 4.30 to 5.30, I'd tell on the drill field.
And then we'd get back, wash up, and it wouldn't be long before it'd be the mess call for supper.
And then we'd formation again, march to supper.
After supper we had maybe an hour before cold quarters.
And then we went to our rooms.
This guard that was mounted in the morning, they'd mount a guard every morning.
A student with a guard.
Why, they would, for three hours there, during study period at night,
They kept, they'd march around the barracks, around the hall, and you were not disposed to go anywhere out of your room except you could go from your room to the latrine and back to your room.
You couldn't visit from one room to the other.
And the guard was, if he didn't enforce that, well then he was subject to severe penalty, punishment.
And they did for him, they did support him.
So then we had, after we, then they'd blow a release at, I guess it was 10 o'clock.
And at 10.15 or 10.30, whichever it was, well then they would sound taps.
And after the sounding of taps, all lights had to be out within five minutes, with the exception of the seniors.
Seniors could burn their lights at midnight.
When did you find out whether or not your room passed inspection for the day, or how did you find out?
You'd find it out that evening at the evening meal.
They read out what is known as a RAM list, and they'd go right down the line of any RAMs while they'd read them out, starting with A's, Abbott so-and-so, improper dress,
Maybe Abbott was room not in order.
And each one of those carried a certain number of demerits.
And so you would always listen at the evening meal to see if your name was on the ram list.
If you got a certain number of rams, you could get them off by walking the bullpen with your rifle.
So many hours, so many rams, and so many hours to take off.
And you had to hold these rams down, because if you got too many rams, you were expelled.
And the way to keep from getting expelled was walk the bullring and get them off.
What was the food like in the mess hall?
Did you have many complaints about it?
Oh, I guess not.
The table manners were bad.
The hard part of the meal was on Thursday night we always got steaks.
That was a big deal, Thursday night.
And was it, did you have a lot of variety or?
The meal was all right.
Old man Speezer was a Spaniard.
That hall was named after him, Old Speezer.
He was the head, what do you call him, head of the- Stewart, I believe.
Stewart, I guess.
Called for a long time.
And we didn't have cadet waiters.
He employed a bunch of Mexican boys.
He had Mexican waiters.
All four years I was there.
I'm interested to hear you say that, because I was about to ask you about students, if there were any students who worked in the mess hall as they have been for later on.
Oh, I'm sure, yes, I know they did.
What was life like in the dormitory where you lived?
I know you said at night they posted a guard, but what about during the day if
If students who were not in class, did they go back to their dormitory rooms, or was everybody in class from 8 till 12?
Well, no, no.
You'd have hours off like you did in high school.
Go wherever you want to during the day if you weren't in class.
What kind of furniture did you have in your dormitory?
Oh, we had a table, two beds, two chairs,
A lot of us, we'd always go down to the secondhand store and buy us an old dresser.
We wanted something extra.
I went to the secondhand store and got me a dresser that I kept for four years.
Left it down there, I guess.
Somebody else left it.
What dormitories did you live in?
I was three years on the top floor of Leggett Hall, which is still being used, I understand.
And then my senior year, I was on the second floor of Milner Hall.
I believe that hall is still being used.
Okay, did they, you said something about earlier about having, being able to get an excuse from during quiet time to go to the latrine.
Did you have one on every floor of the dorms or did you have a separate building for that?
No, in Leggett Hall, Mildenhall, both there was a central latrine.
On each floor?
Oh yeah.
What privileges did the upperclassmen have that the freshmen didn't enjoy?
The first year, the freshmen could go to town on Saturday afternoon.
There was a car there that ran the town.
And the freshmen would go to town on Saturday afternoon, but they had to be back in time for the evening meal roll call.
A sophomore could go to town two nights a month.
That would be in addition to Saturday afternoon.
Saturday afternoon.
A sophomore could go two nights a month.
A junior could go four nights a month.
Saturday nights, not during the week night, but he could go Saturday night.
Every night as a junior.
And seniors
go and come at will whenever and wherever they wanted to.
Seniors ran that outfit, senior officers, the captain of your company, lieutenants, and they ran the school.
They would.
You had to get permission from them or anything.
What sort of things did the freshmen have to do for the upperclassmen?
Well, of course, hazing was quite prevalent then, and they had to run errands for them, and they had to address them as mister, and that's why they got the paddle pretty heavy.
Of course, hazing was against the rules, and if you caught hazing while you were expelled,
but somehow they never did catch very many of them.
Was that a permanent expulsion or just a temporary one?
No, they were expelled from school for hazing.
No, I was wondering whether they were just expelled say for the rest of the semester or whether they were allowed to come back.
I guess maybe they could come back the next year probably if they'd come back and apologize.
I don't know, but I know that, oh there was, I don't know how many were expelled a year, maybe 10 or 15.
I don't know.
There were a lot more of them than that did hazing, I take it.
There's about 15 that didn't do hazing, I think.
Okay, you mentioned running errands.
Would this be going to the laundry?
Well, they delivered the laundry.
No, you'd have to go down to the drug store to get a cigar or just anything that a sophomore wanted to do.
Sophomores did most of the hazing.
And the juniors, the sophomores, they're the ones that carried the big battle.
The juniors in Nazareth, they were more mature.
Of course, if they wanted anything, they had the best fish to go do something for them.
And the seniors didn't do any hazing at all.
But nevertheless, they pretty well controlled things.
Oh, yes.
He was a commissioned officer of your company.
Did you, did they still have wood stoves in the dorms?
Did you have to go get wood and things like that for them?
Did they have central heating?
No, in Leggett Hall and Millnau and all of this, it was central heating.
Central heating.
Radiators.
I guess that still is.
Yeah, I see.
Okay.
What did the students do for entertainment and recreation, like what they did when they weren't in class?
Well, they had the intramural athletics.
Did most of them participate in that?
No, I'd say they did.
I don't know what percentage.
How was that arranged?
Was that on a company basis?
Each company had the athletic baseball team, or football team, yes.
There's about a hundred, or about seventy-five in each company.
And the football team would be at least eleven.
That's right.
Well, they'd play.
I was in Company L and Company L would play the other company you wanted.
So did you play for a regular championship then among the various companies?
Oh yes.
It was a competition to see who was the top intramural team.
A lot of them would make good in the intramural team.
they would go down and get on the varsity team.
The coaches watched them.
Well, what about dances or things of that nature?
Well, the freshmen didn't go to any dances.
But the three of the class, they'd have dances.
And of course, the seniors were.
We had dances.
Got all the girls from Brown.
Many of them bring the girls from their hometowns?
Quite often.
Quite often.
After you got up to be in that class one time.
The girl would be a guest or a friend of yours, maybe a professor or somebody on the campus.
They'd let the girls stay with them while they were doing the dance.
Did the girls ever stay in some of the dormitories?
At one point I understood that sometimes they would throw all the boys out of one of the dormitories and put all the girls up.
My time, my time.
Primarily they stayed with faculty members.
That's faculty members.
At that point I believe they all lived on campus, didn't they?
Or almost all of them anyway.
The campus?
Yeah.
The faculty?
Faculty, yeah.
Okay.
You mentioned that you could go down to Bryan occasionally.
For what purpose did people go down to Bryan?
Oh, go to the big show or just get away from the campus on Saturday afternoon.
Go down there and play pool.
I believe I heard Mr. Langford say that one of the reasons the school was located where it was, as far away from Bryan as it was, was to get away from the saloons in Bryan.
Did any of the boys go down there to partake of the... Bryan was dry.
It was dry at that time.
Yeah, dry when I was there.
They got all the liquor down there across the river.
Burleson County, that's where it was.
But I'll say this.
In four years there, I would say that I didn't see five, I don't know, but very, very few drunk cadets.
They didn't drink.
They didn't keep liquor in the rooms.
I never saw a boy have liquor in his room.
Well, that was a pretty serious offense for one thing, wasn't it?
Oh, it was an expulsion, absolutely.
They'd do some little drinking.
Now every year, they'd take the Corps to Dallas Fair.
And we'd parade down the street there in Dallas, go up on a special train, early morning train, at the ball game.
I've seen some boys that got a little liquored up at Dallas, but might have probably stayed.

No, but back to what I was saying earlier, Mr. Lankford, either he or somebody else said that in 76 when they started the school, I think there were 12 saloons in Bryan, and at that point I would imagine that that would have been an unfortunate... Well, they bought the dry after that, you see.
Brazos County was dry when I was... Wellesley County, of course, the river was wet.
Yeah.
That was, I guess, just since I'd been there, Brazos County.
Well, they sold beer, but they didn't have any liquor stores, and they still had one just across the bridge going out of College Station.
Did they also go to Bryan to shop, or could they buy everything they needed on campus?
Oh, you could buy whatever you need down there.
Cosmetics, toothpaste, and et cetera.
But they weren't any good stores at the college station.
You weren't going to buy any clothes, extra clothes.
Of course, you had to wear a uniform all the time, both on the campus and off the campus, those gray uniforms.
Where did you get those?
They issued them to you, except

When you got to be an upperclassman, there's an old tailor there named Charlie Hulligan, and he would, as you got to be an upperclassman, you wanted to be a little better dressed instead of issue stuff.
Well, Charlie made most of the uniforms for the upperclassmen, tailor-made.
What would a full uniform have cost you?
There was a confectionery, I believe, in the basement of the YMCA, was there not?
Or did that come along later?
No, it came along later.
There was a confectionery down there, a little frame building down there, where the trolley car stopped, down there close to Speezer Hall.
Was there a station where the trolley car stopped?
No, no station.
Was there a platform or anything to get under when you waited for the train?
No, you run into the trucks and run into the perfection yard.
You mentioned earlier that the seniors really sort of
ran the Corps of Cadets, were there any special privileges that they said the cadet officers had?
Say, could a junior cadet officer, who was a higher ranking officer than, say, a fellow junior, did he have any privileges?
You're a freshman of all privates, see.
And the sophomores who did good, did well, were the corporals.
And the juniors were the sergeants.
Not all juniors.
I mean, the top juniors, they were sergeants.
And then the seniors were the commissioned officers.
That'd be for everything from lieutenant on up.
That's right.
And then, of course, they had the staff.
They went on up to staff officers, majors, lieutenant colonels, and colonels.
Yeah.
OK.
So then, basically, all sophomores were in the same military rank.
Yes.
and all juniors.
And the seniors were the only ones who had higher ranks.
That's right.
They were all privates.
And they had some senior privates that didn't qualify to be commissioned officers.
And they were just, well, they didn't have anything to do with
But they were called senior privates.
They didn't have any formations to make.
All they did was sleep mean.
Well, they didn't have to make formations for breakfast?
Not the senior privates.
No, they didn't have to make any.
What about drill?
Did they have to do any drill at all?
No.
Were there any students
there, when you were there, who were not in the Corps of Cadets.
No.
Even the, you take the disabled boys, they gave them, most of them were buglers, taught them to blow the bugle.
Each company had a bugler.
And the boy was disabled, couldn't participate in his drill, his uniform, and his drills were
They would designate him as a bugler and took him out there and showed him how to blow the bugle.
And then he would do all the signals then in the morning and each meal?
Well, they would designate one bugler as the bugler of the week and had a big microphone, I mean loudspeaker there that did bugle over.
They wouldn't all blow the bugle all the time.
They'd just have a bugle of the week or the bugle of the day.
They'd want to make just one man would do all that bugling.
Okay, I think I'm about out of space here.
Let me...
